For garments with prints or embellishments, turn them inside out before washing and ironing. This protects the design from damage and fading.
Bleach should only be used on white cottons and linens, and always with caution. Check the care label to ensure the fabric is bleach-safe.
If you spill something on your clothing, act quickly. Blot the stain, don't rub, and rinse with cold water from the back of the fabric to push it out.
Air drying is best for delicate fabrics and items prone to shrinking. Hang sweaters flat to dry to maintain their shape and avoid stretching.
Fabric softeners can make your clothes feel softer and reduce static cling. Add them during the rinse cycle for optimal results.
For delicate embellishments or sequins, turn the garment inside out before washing to protect them from snagging or damage.
Steaming clothes is an excellent alternative to ironing for quick wrinkle removal. It's gentle on fabrics and perfect for travel.
Always close zippers and fasten hooks before washing to prevent them from snagging other items in the load. This protects your clothes.
