While learning, you might find it easier to stand in front of a mirror. Seeing your grip helps you correct your hand placement until it feels comfortable and very secure daily.
If the floss keeps slipping from your fingers, you might need to wrap it more times. A secure knot or extra loops can help maintain the tension you need for cleaning.
Always leave about one or two inches of floss to work with between your hands. This short length makes it much easier to guide the floss around the curves of teeth.
If you struggle with the grip, you can try using a plastic floss holder. This tool helps people who have limited dexterity or difficulty reaching the back teeth during cleaning.
Rotate the floss to a clean section as you move from one tooth to the next. This prevents you from spreading bacteria back into other areas of your clean mouth.
Hold the floss firmly between your fingers to prevent it from slipping. A steady grip is essential to apply the right amount of pressure against the surfaces of your teeth.
Many patients find that wrapping the floss around the middle fingers provides the best stability. This leaves your index fingers free to manipulate the floss into those hard to reach spots.
